<item>
            <title>[DERBY-3333] User name corresponding to authentication identifier PUBLIC must be rejected</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/DERBY-3333</link>
                <project id="10594" key="DERBY">Derby</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;SQL Standard (foundation) says:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Section 5.4 SR 20) No &amp;lt;authorization identifier&amp;gt; shall specify &quot;PUBLIC&quot;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is a syntax rule which implies a 42xxx SQL state but I wonder if &apos;invalid authorization specification.&apos; (28xxx) makes more sense?&lt;br/&gt;
Maybe it&apos;s 28xxx when used in a connection request and 42xxx in a SQL statement?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Needs to be disallowed on:&lt;br/&gt;
  JDBC connection requests&lt;br/&gt;
  GRANT statements, ie. using &quot;PUBLIC&quot; as a delimited identifier.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Existing application impact if the exists a user with an authorization identifier of PUBLIC in an existing system.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
